{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507086"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:49:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:49:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2599"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2599"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.12,0.09,0.51,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2599"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43507"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2599"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2599"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28508"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"307"},{"type":"tags","id":"1138"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44526"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43507"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a painless, slow-growing mass on the side of his face first noticed six months ago. It does not fluctuate with meals and systems review is negative for dysphagia, hoarseness and constitutional symptoms of malignancy. He has a medical history of hypertension and previous cholecystectomy. He takes no regular medications. He has never smoked and does not drink alcohol. On examination, there is a firm, mobile mass inferior to the left ear measuring 3x2 cm. There are no masses of the oral cavity. Cranial nerve examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Branchial cleft cyst","Warthin tumour","Obstructed submandibular gland","Pleomorphic adenoma of the parotid","Lipoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history of a painless, slow-growing mass affecting the parotid region is consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Epleomorphic adenoma of the parotid\u003C/strong\u003E. These masses are generally benign, however may undergo malignant change. Features of malignant change would include rapid enlargement or features of local infiltration such as dysphagia, hoarseness or facial nerve involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarthin tumours\u003C/strong\u003E are the second most common mass affecting the parotid gland. They appear in a similar demographic but are strongly associated with smoking and radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipoma \u003C/strong\u003Eis a reasonable differential for this mass given the history and appearance. However, lipomas of the head and neck are uncommon. Lipomas of the head and neck most commonly occur in the posterior triangle. Although this picture could be consistent with a lipoma of the parotid gland, these are particularly rare. Core needle biopsy would be required to exclude this definitively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalculi may cause \u003Cstrong\u003Eobstruction of the submandibular gland\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as sialolithiasis. On examination, a mass may be present below the angle of the jaw. However, this mass would typically be painful and fluctuate with meals. In some cases, the obstructing stone may be visible in the oral cavity at the orifice of the submandibular duct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebranchial cleft cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital anomaly caused by failure obliteration of one or more of the branchial clefts during embryological development. It is an common causes of a neck mass in children and it would be rare for one to go undetected beyond early adulthood.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Most swellings in the region of the parotid gland are pleomorphic adenomas."],"references":["Kim K, Yang W. Unusual locations of lipoma: differential diagnosis of head and neck mass. Aust Fam Physician. 2014;43(12):867-870. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25705737/","Teh A, Kumar A, Teh C, Alhilali L. Overview of Parotid Gland Masses. J Am Osteopath Coll Radiol. 2018;7(4):5-10. Available at: https://www.aocr.org/page/JAOCRIssues"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28508"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2599"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15306"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15306"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0e2dca9d-74c2-4a95-988e-5f22338035fc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0e2dca9d-74c2-4a95-988e-5f22338035fc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28508"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-20T12:13:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-20T12:13:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2599"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43507"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[